const BLURBS = {
  1: "DNA Polymerase Beta is your cell’s tireless repair crew. It patches up damaged DNA, fixing roughly 20,000 lesions per cell every single day. This unsung hero keeps your genetic code intact.",
  2: "Meet the SH3 Domain, a master of protein networking. This tiny module pops up in hundreds of signaling proteins, orchestrating critical cellular conversations. It’s a cornerstone of molecular communication.",
  3: "DNA Polymerase I holds a historic spot in science as the first of its kind identified. Its discovery by Arthur Kornberg in 1959 clinched a Nobel Prize, marking a genetic breakthrough. A true pioneer enzyme!",
  4: "Insulin rules blood sugar with an iron fist as a vital hormone. It became the first protein to have its amino acid sequence cracked by Frederick Sanger in 1951. A landmark in biochemistry!",
  5: "Taq Polymerase thrives under heat, fueling the PCR revolution. Sourced from a hot spring bacterium, it’s the engine behind modern DNA testing. Science owes it a huge debt.",
  6: "Tumor Necrosis Factor wields power as an inflammatory cytokine that can slay cancer cells. Blocking it has transformed treatments for arthritis and Crohn’s disease. A double-edged sword in medicine!",
  7: "RNA Polymerase II transcribes DNA into messenger RNA with precision. Its intricate structure earned Roger Kornberg, son of Arthur, a Nobel Prize. A family legacy in genetic machinery!",
  8: "Ras GTPase acts as a cellular growth switch, flipping critical signals. Alarmingly, it’s mutated in 30% of human cancers, making it a prime research target. A tiny protein with massive impact.",
  9: "Bacterial RNA Polymerase reads bacterial genes like a pro. It’s the prime target of rifampicin, a key antibiotic for tuberculosis treatment. A vulnerable spot in microbial defenses!",
  10: "Epidermal Growth Factor sparks cell growth and heals wounds with flair. Its discovery by Stanley Cohen earned a 1986 Nobel Prize. A catalyst for regeneration!",
  11: "tRNA Synthetase plays matchmaker, linking amino acids to tRNA. With 20 unique versions—one per amino acid—it’s a cornerstone of protein building. Precision at its finest!",
  12: "Lac Repressor flips the switch on gene regulation with classic style. Its discovery by Jacob and Monod secured a Nobel Prize, shaping molecular biology. A textbook icon!",
  13: "The Ribosome’s Large Subunit builds proteins from mRNA blueprints. Its detailed structure, unveiled by Venki Ramakrishnan, won a 2009 Nobel. A factory of life itself!",
  14: "Crambin, a small plant protein, stands as a structural superstar. Boasting one of the highest resolution protein models ever, it’s a crystallographer’s dream. Tiny but mighty!",
  15: "The Ribosome’s Small Subunit decodes genetic instructions during translation. It’s a frequent target for antibiotics, disrupting bacterial protein synthesis. A chink in microbial armor!",
  16: "VEGF drives blood vessel growth, a key player in cancer therapy. Blocking it starves tumors by slashing their blood supply. A strategic weapon against malignancy!",
  17: "Helicase unzips the DNA double helix with molecular finesse. Acting like a tiny zipper, it paves the way for replication and repair. Pure mechanical genius!",
  18: "Nuclear Receptors bind steroid hormones to steer cellular responses. This family spans receptors for steroids, thyroid hormones, and vitamin D. A versatile regulatory squad!",
  19: "Topoisomerase I eases DNA supercoiling stress with surgical precision. It’s a prime target for cancer drugs like topotecan, halting rogue replication. A therapeutic bullseye!",
  20: "Trp Repressor fine-tunes tryptophan synthesis genes with elegance. It’s a textbook case of feedback regulation in action. Control at the molecular level!",
  21: "Gyrase twists DNA into negative supercoils, shaping its structure. As a target for fluoroquinolone antibiotics, it’s a bacterial Achilles’ heel. A critical weak point!",
  22: "Prion Protein, normally benign in the brain, can turn deadly when misfolded. Its rogue form triggers mad cow disease and CJD, a chilling transformation. A biological Jekyll and Hyde!",
  23: "Base Excision Repair Enzyme snips out damaged DNA bases to save the day. Its discovery by Tomas Lindahl earned a 2015 Nobel Prize. A guardian of genetic integrity!",
  24: "Growth Hormone spurs growth and cell renewal with potent force. It was the first human protein crafted via genetic engineering in 1979. A biotech trailblazer!",
  25: "Nucleotide Excision Repair slices out bulky DNA damage with precision. Defects in this system cause xeroderma pigmentosum, triggering extreme sun sensitivity. A shield against UV havoc!",
  26: "Your body’s stress manager, the Glucocorticoid Receptor, binds cortisol to dial down inflammation. It’s the target of drugs like prednisone, mimicking natural steroids to calm immune overreactions. Discovered in 2002, it’s a key player in balancing stress and immunity.",
  27: "Xanthine Oxidase is the culprit behind uric acid buildup, sparking painful gout attacks. Gout drugs like allopurinol shut it down, preventing crystal formation in joints. Discovered in 2004, it’s a prime target for relief.",
  28: "Cro Repressor acts like a genetic toggle switch in bacteriophage lambda, controlling viral gene expression. It’s one of the tiniest DNA-binding proteins known, packing precision into a small package. Discovered in 1988, it’s a minimalist marvel of regulation.",
  29: "Telomerase is the cellular fountain of youth, extending chromosome ends to prevent aging decay. Active in cancer and stem cells, it’s a double-edged sword in disease and repair. Discovered in 2007, its study clinched a 2009 Nobel Prize.",
  30: "Alpha-Synuclein clumps into toxic Lewy bodies, the hallmark of Parkinson’s disease. Found in 2004, this brain protein’s misfolding disrupts neurons, driving tremors and loss of movement. It’s a prime suspect in neurodegenerative research.",
  31: "Lactate Dehydrogenase turns pyruvate into lactate, explaining that muscle burn during a brutal workout. Discovered in 1994, it’s your body’s quick fix for energy when oxygen runs low. No pain, no gain, right?",
  32: "WNT Protein steers embryo development and stem cell fate with uncanny precision. Its quirky name blends ‘wingless’ from flies and ‘int-1’ from mice, reflecting its discovery history. Found in 2012, it’s a master architect of life.",
  33: "Glyceraldehyde-3-P Dehydrogenase is a glycolysis workhorse, breaking down sugar for energy. Beyond metabolism, it sneaks into the nucleus to tweak gene expression. Discovered in 1995, it’s a surprising multitasker.",
  34: "The Estrogen Receptor drives female hormone effects and is a key target in breast cancer. Drugs like tamoxifen block it, halting cancer growth in many patients. Discovered in 1997, it’s a linchpin in hormone therapy.",
  35: "Pyruvate Kinase caps glycolysis by churning out ATP, fueling your cells. Cancer cells often revert to an embryonic form of it, hijacking metabolism for rapid growth. Discovered in 1994, it’s a hotspot for tumor research.",
  36: "Zinc Finger domains grip DNA with metal-coordinated precision, guiding gene regulation. They powered early gene-editing tools before CRISPR stole the spotlight. Discovered in 1991, they’re still a fundamental design in biotech.",
  37: "Aldolase slices sugars in glycolysis, named for the aldol condensation reaction it mirrors. Discovered in 1995, it’s a critical gear in the cellular energy machine. Without it, metabolism would grind to a halt.",
  38: "Amyloid Beta aggregates into brain plaques, the notorious hallmark of Alzheimer’s disease. Billions have been spent trying to clear these toxic clusters, with mixed success. Discovered in 2007, it remains a frustrating puzzle.",
  39: "Triose Phosphate Isomerase is a catalytic superstar, often called a perfectly evolved enzyme. It speeds sugar breakdown in glycolysis with near-flawless efficiency. Discovered in 1975, it’s a textbook case of biochemical perfection.",
  40: "Calmodulin is the universal calcium sensor, orchestrating countless cell processes. Nearly identical across all animals, its conservation speaks to its critical role. Discovered in 1988, it’s a cornerstone of cellular signaling.",
  41: "Citrate Synthase kicks off the citric acid cycle, merging molecules to fuel energy production. It undergoes a dramatic shape shift when binding substrates, a molecular dance of precision. Discovered in 1991, it’s a metabolic gatekeeper.",
  42: "The Androgen Receptor binds testosterone, fueling male traits and, sometimes, prostate cancer. Drugs that block it are frontline treatments for this cancer. Discovered in 2001, it’s a critical target in oncology.",
  43: "Aconitase reshapes molecules in the citric acid cycle while moonlighting as an iron sensor. When iron levels drop, it shifts gears to regulate metabolism. Discovered in 1996, it’s a dual-threat in energy and homeostasis.",
  44: "Homeodomain proteins dictate body plans, from fly wings to human limbs, over 600 million years. Their startling similarity across species reveals deep evolutionary roots. Discovered in 1990, they’re architects of anatomy.",
  45: "Aspartate Aminotransferase (AST) spikes in blood when liver or heart tissue is damaged. Used as a diagnostic marker, it signals trouble in vital organs. Discovered in 1984, it’s a clinical red flag.",
  46: "Tau Protein forms tangles in Alzheimer’s, strangling neurons in devastating dementias. Some evidence suggests these tangles spread like an infection through the brain. Discovered in 1999, it’s a key focus in neurodegeneration.",
  47: "Alanine Aminotransferase (ALT) is a blood test staple, pinpointing liver damage with high specificity. Unlike AST, it’s more tied to liver woes than heart issues. Discovered in 1995, it’s a diagnostic precision tool.",
  48: "Sonic Hedgehog protein shapes embryos, guiding limbs and organs with eerie accuracy. Named after the video game icon by a whimsical scientist, it’s pure serious business. Discovered in 1999, it’s a developmental rockstar.",
  49: "Urate Oxidase breaks down uric acid in most mammals, but humans lost this gene. That evolutionary glitch leaves us prone to gout’s painful crystals. Discovered in 1996, it’s a missing shield in our metabolism.",
  50: "Retinoid X Receptor binds vitamin A derivatives, steering gene expression in growth and vision. It often teams up with other nuclear receptors for broader impact. Discovered in 1995, it’s a versatile regulator.",
  51: "Your body’s detox hero, arginase, turns toxic ammonia into harmless urea in the final step of the urea cycle. Without it, ammonia would build up and wreak havoc on your brain and organs. Discovered in 1999, it’s a silent guardian of metabolic balance.",
  52: "The SARS-CoV-2 spike protein is the key that COVID-19 uses to unlock and invade human cells. Its structure was decoded in a record-breaking 12 days after the virus sequence was released in 2020. This rapid solve fueled vaccine development at warp speed.",
  53: "Ornithine transcarbamylase is a urea cycle enzyme, and its deficiency is the most common defect in this pathway. Linked to an X-chromosome disorder, it can cause dangerous ammonia buildup. Discovered in 1990, it’s a critical piece of metabolic machinery.",
  54: "TATA binding protein is the maestro of gene expression, bending DNA nearly 90 degrees to kickstart transcription. This dramatic twist exposes the genetic code for reading. Discovered in 1993, it’s a pivotal player in cellular storytelling.",
  55: "Phenylalanine hydroxylase is vital for breaking down the amino acid phenylalanine, but when defective, it causes phenylketonuria (PKU). That’s why every newborn is screened for PKU to prevent severe neurological damage. Discovered in 1999, it’s a small enzyme with big consequences.",
  56: "Collagen, the most abundant protein in your body, builds the scaffolding for skin, bones, and tendons. Making up 30% of your protein content, it’s also the key ingredient in gelatin. Discovered in 1954, it’s literally holding you together.",
  57: "Tyrosinase crafts melanin, the pigment behind your skin, hair, and eye color. Defects in this enzyme lead to albinism, a lack of pigmentation. Discovered in 2004, it’s the artist of your natural hues.",
  58: "Amylin, a hormone co-secreted with insulin, helps regulate appetite and blood glucose levels. It works behind the scenes to balance your metabolism. Discovered in 2001, it’s a subtle but key player in energy control.",
  59: "DOPA decarboxylase transforms L-DOPA into dopamine, a crucial brain chemical. It’s the reason L-DOPA works as a Parkinson’s treatment, replenishing lost dopamine. Discovered in 2001, it’s a lifeline for movement and mood.",
  60: "The vitamin D receptor translates vitamin D’s signals into action, controlling calcium and bone health. Fun fact: active vitamin D is technically a hormone, not just a vitamin. Discovered in 2000, it’s a master of mineral balance.",
  61: "Tryptophan hydroxylase is the gatekeeper of serotonin production, a neurotransmitter tied to mood. Genetic variants in this enzyme are linked to depression risk. Discovered in 2007, it’s a key to understanding mental health chemistry.",
  62: "Hemagglutinin, a surface protein on influenza viruses, latches onto your cells to start  start an infection. It’s the ‘H’ in flu strain names like H1N1. Discovered in 1981, it’s the flu’s handshake of doom.",
  63: "Monoamine oxidase breaks down neurotransmitters like serotonin and dopamine, keeping brain chemistry in check. Its inhibitors were the first antidepressants, revolutionizing mental health treatment. Discovered in 2002, it’s a target for mood-altering meds.",
  64: "Pancreatic trypsin inhibitor shields your pancreas from digesting itself by blocking rogue enzymes. It’s also the most studied small protein for understanding protein folding. Discovered in 1973, it’s a tiny protector with big research impact.",
  65: "Cyclooxygenase-1 (COX-1) produces prostaglandins, signaling molecules tied to pain and inflammation, and aspirin permanently shuts it down. This irreversible block is why aspirin relieves aches so well. Discovered in 1994, it’s a cornerstone of pain relief.",
  66: "Histone H3 wraps DNA into tight packages, playing a central role in gene regulation. It’s one of the most conserved proteins across evolution, barely changing over billions of years. Discovered in 1997, it’s a timeless guardian of genetic code.",
  67: "Cyclooxygenase-2 (COX-2) drives inflammation and is a prime target for NSAIDs like Celebrex, which spare the stomach unlike broader drugs. It’s a key player in pain and swelling responses. Discovered in 1996, it’s a precision strike against discomfort.",
  68: "Leptin, the ‘satiety hormone,’ signals your brain to stop eating and revs up metabolism. Mice without it balloon into extreme obesity, showing its power. Discovered in 1997, it’s a master controller of body weight.",
  69: "Lipoxygenase churns out leukotrienes, molecules that fuel inflammation and are linked to asthma attacks. Drugs like zileuton target it to ease breathing. Discovered in 1993, it’s a hidden driver of allergic and inflammatory chaos.",
  70: "Rhodopsin, the light receptor in your eyes, can detect a single photon, making vision possible even in dim light. It’s the cornerstone of how we see the world. Discovered in 2000, it’s a marvel of sensory precision.",
  71: "Nitric oxide synthase produces NO, a tiny gas molecule that signals blood vessels to relax. Viagra boosts NO’s effects, explaining its famous action. Discovered in 1998, it’s a key to cardiovascular and other vital functions.",
  72: "Neuraminidase, an influenza enzyme, helps the virus escape infected cells, and it’s the target of drugs like Tamiflu. It’s the ‘N’ in flu strain names like H1N1. Discovered in 1983, it’s a getaway driver for viral spread.",
  73: "Aromatase converts testosterone into estrogen, a critical step in hormone balance. Inhibitors of this enzyme are frontline treatments for breast cancer. Discovered in 1997, it’s a pivotal switch in the body’s chemical dance.",
  74: "Alpha-amylase inhibitor blocks starch digestion, slowing sugar absorption in the gut. Compounds mimicking it are used in diet pills to curb calorie intake. Discovered in 1993, it’s a gatekeeper of carb breakdown.",
  75: "HMG-CoA reductase is the rate-limiting enzyme in cholesterol synthesis, and statins, the world’s best-selling drugs, block it. This shutdown slashes cholesterol levels and heart disease risk. Discovered in 2000, it’s a blockbuster target for health.",
  76: "Tubulin forms the highways of the cell, building microtubules for structure and transport. Cancer drugs like taxol target it, freezing cell division in its tracks.",
  77: "Cytochrome P450 3A4 metabolizes half of all drugs we take. Watch out for grapefruit—it blocks this enzyme, risking dangerous drug interactions.",
  78: "Annexin V latches onto dying cells by binding exposed phosphatidylserine. It’s a go-to tool for spotting cell death in labs and clinics.",
  79: "Cytochrome P450 2D6 handles 25% of drug metabolism. Genetic quirks in some people slow it down, messing with drug effectiveness.",
  80: "GLUT1 ferries glucose into cells, fueling life. A deficiency starves the brain of energy, triggering seizures.",
  81: "Glycogen Phosphorylase breaks down glycogen to free up glucose. It’s a textbook case of enzyme control via phosphorylation.",
  82: "Beta-2 Adrenergic Receptor catches adrenaline and powers asthma drugs. Its study snagged a 2012 Nobel Prize for Kobilka and Lefkowitz.",
  83: "Glycogen Synthase builds glycogen to store energy after meals. Insulin flips the switch to turn it on.",
  84: "HIV-1 Capsid forms the shell of HIV, protecting its core. It’s now a target for lenacapavir, a promising injectable HIV drug.",
  85: "Glucose-6-Phosphatase releases glucose from the liver into the bloodstream. It’s the final gatekeeper for blood sugar levels.",
  86: "Sodium Channel sparks electrical signals in nerves. Local anesthetics like lidocaine block it, numbing pain on the spot.",
  87: "FKBP12 binds the drug tacrolimus, enabling immunosuppression. It’s a key player in preventing organ rejection after transplants.",
  88: "Avidin, from egg whites, grips biotin with unmatched strength. Labs use it as a molecular superglue for experiments.",
  89: "Superoxide Dismutase wipes out toxic superoxide radicals. Mutations in it are linked to ALS, also known as Lou Gehrig’s disease.",
  90: "Green Fluorescent Protein (GFP) glows green under UV, straight from jellyfish. It revolutionized cell biology, earning a 2008 Nobel and lighting up countless experiments.",
  91: "RuBisCO, Earth’s most abundant protein, turns CO2 into sugar for plants. With 700 million tons worldwide, every carbon in your body once passed through it.",
  92: "Actin, a cellular heavyweight, forms the cytoskeleton in many cells. In muscles, it accounts for 15% of total protein.",
  93: "Catalase obliterates hydrogen peroxide, protecting cells. It’s why peroxide bubbles when cleaning a cut.",
  94: "Bence Jones Protein, an antibody fragment from myeloma patients, made history. It was the first human protein structure ever solved.",
  95: "Glutathione Peroxidase, a rare selenium-containing enzyme, fights oxidative damage. It’s one of the few proteins packing this unusual element.",
  96: "REG3A, a gut defender, kills bacteria by puncturing their walls. Think of it as your intestine’s personal antibiotic.",
  97: "Glutathione S-Transferase detoxifies harmful compounds in cells. It shields against drugs and environmental toxins.",
  98: "GLUT4 ramps up glucose uptake in response to insulin. After eating, insulin pushes more GLUT4 to muscle cell surfaces.",
  99: "Cyclin-Dependent Kinase 2 drives the cell cycle and is a cancer drug target. Its role in cell division earned a Nobel Prize.",
  100: "Dopamine D3 Receptor in the brain ties to reward, addiction, and Parkinson’s. It’s also a target for schizophrenia treatments.",
  101: "Aurora Kinase orchestrates the delicate dance of chromosome separation during cell division. Named after the mesmerizing aurora borealis for its glowing role in mitosis, it’s a prime target for cancer drugs. Discovered in 2004, this protein could unlock new ways to stop uncontrolled cell growth.",
  102: "GroEL Chaperonin is a barrel-shaped cage that rescues misfolded proteins. Think of it as a washing machine, tumbling proteins back into their proper shape to keep cells functional. Discovered in 1994, it’s a critical player in protein quality control.",
  103: "Caspase-3 is the grim reaper of cells, executing programmed cell death. It slices through proteins with precision, ensuring the cell dismantles itself systematically. Discovered in 2003, it’s a key to understanding apoptosis and disease.",
  104: "Zika Virus Envelope protein studs the surface of the Zika virus, enabling infection. Notorious for causing microcephaly in newborns, it’s a critical target for vaccines. Discovered in 2016, it underscores the urgency of viral research.",
  105: "Caspase-9 kicks off the intrinsic pathway of cell death, acting as an initiator of doom. It’s activated by cytochrome c leaking from damaged mitochondria, setting off a fatal cascade. Discovered in 2001, it’s central to cellular self-destruction.",
  106: "Calcium Channels are gatekeepers, controlling calcium entry in muscles and neurons for vital signaling. They’re targets for blood pressure meds, tweaking flow to ease strain on the heart. Discovered in 2015, they’re key to excitable cell function.",
  107: "Ferritin is your body’s iron vault, storing up to 4500 iron atoms in a hollow ball. It keeps toxic iron safely locked away, preventing cellular damage. Discovered in 1991, it’s essential for iron balance.",
  108: "DFF/CAD Nuclease shreds DNA during apoptosis, marking a cell’s final farewell. Its cuts create a distinct DNA ladder pattern, a hallmark of programmed death. Discovered in 1998, it’s a grim but necessary executioner.",
  109: "Huntingtin, when mutated, triggers the devastating Huntington’s disease. Extra CAG repeats lead to a toxic polyglutamine expansion, wreaking havoc in the brain. Discovered in 2012, it’s a focal point for neurodegenerative research.",
  110: "Titin is the heavyweight champ of proteins, the largest known, giving muscles their elasticity. Its full chemical name, at 189,819 letters, is the longest word in English. Discovered in 2006, it’s a giant in muscle biology.",
  111: "Immunoglobulin G (IgG) is the most abundant antibody in your blood, fighting off invaders. Its Y-shaped design inspired the ‘magic bullet’ concept in medicine for targeted attacks. Discovered in 1977, it’s a cornerstone of immunity.",
  112: "Nerve Growth Factor, the first neurotrophin identified, supports neuron survival and growth. Its discovery earned Rita Levi-Montalcini a Nobel Prize for pioneering neuroscience. Discovered in 1991, it’s vital for nervous system health.",
  113: "Sodium-Glucose Cotransporter reabsorbs glucose in the kidney, a target for diabetes drugs. SGLT2 inhibitors force glucose out through urine, a clever metabolic hack. Discovered in 2012, it’s reshaping diabetes treatment.",
  114: "Opioid Receptor governs pain and pleasure, binding morphine and similar drugs. Overactivation can spiral into addiction, a sobering downside of relief. Discovered in 2012, it’s at the heart of the opioid crisis.",
  115: "Hsp70 is a stress-response protein that refolds others under pressure. Heat shock proteins like this were stumbled upon by accident in 1962. Discovered in 2005, it’s a cellular lifeline during tough times.",
  116: "Dengue Virus Envelope protein coats the dengue fever virus, infecting 400 million people annually. It’s the key to viral entry and a prime vaccine target. Discovered in 2013, it drives urgent global health efforts.",
  117: "CFTR is a chloride channel, and its mutations cause cystic fibrosis lung issues. New drugs can now repair some faulty CFTR versions, offering hope. Discovered in 2017, it’s a breakthrough for genetic disease treatment.",
  118: "Myosin is the molecular motor behind muscle contraction, pulling with a force of 10 piconewtons. It powers every flex and step you take. Discovered in 1993, it’s the engine of movement.",
  119: "Ovalbumin dominates egg whites, making up most of their protein content. A common allergen, it’s also a lab standard for protein studies. Discovered in 1991, it’s both culinary and scientific staple.",
  120: "Chlorophyll Binding Protein captures light for photosynthesis, making plants green. It absorbs red and blue light, reflecting the green we see. Discovered in 2004, it’s the heart of plant energy conversion.",
  121: "Carbonic Anhydrase zips CO2 into bicarbonate in blood, balancing pH at lightning speed. Clocking up to 1 million reactions per second, it’s among the fastest enzymes. Discovered in 1972, it’s crucial for respiration.",
  122: "BDNF, or Brain-Derived Neurotrophic Factor, boosts brain health and plasticity. Exercise ramps up BDNF levels, lifting mood and memory. Discovered in 1999, it’s a mental wellness powerhouse.",
  123: "Nitrogenase is life’s nitrogen fixer, cracking the tough triple bond of atmospheric N2. It’s the only enzyme with this superpower, fueling plant growth. Discovered in 1992, it’s essential for the biosphere.",
  124: "Neurotrophin-3 drives nerve development, especially for sensory neurons. It shapes how we feel the world through touch and pain. Discovered in 1991, it’s a builder of neural connections.",
  125: "Flavodoxin steps in as an electron carrier in bacteria when iron is scarce. It substitutes for ferredoxin, keeping metabolism humming along. Discovered in 1975, it’s a backup plan for tough conditions.",
  126: "Imagine a protein as a lifeline for nerve cells. Neurotrophin-4 (NT-4) supports motor neuron survival, ensuring they don’t wither away. Discovered in 1995, it’s a key player in keeping your nervous system wired.",
  127: "Picture a relay race in photosynthesis, passing electrons like batons. Ferredoxin Reductase is the critical link in this chain, powering plants with energy from sunlight. Discovered in 1995, it’s a cornerstone of life’s energy factory.",
  128: "Blood vessels don’t just form—they need a steady hand to stabilize. Angiopoietin steps in to secure these new networks, guiding proper growth. Discovered in 2001, it’s vital for vascular integrity.",
  129: "Older than life as we know it, Ferredoxin is an iron-sulfur protein found in every kingdom of life. It shuttles electrons in processes like photosynthesis and respiration. Discovered in 1992, it’s a relic of ancient biochemistry.",
  130: "Need more red blood cells? Erythropoietin triggers their production in bone marrow, a lifesaver for anemia. Infamously, athletes abuse synthetic EPO for illegal performance boosts. Discovered in 1998, it’s a double-edged sword.",
  131: "Phosphofructokinase-2 is a master switch in glycolysis, controlling sugar breakdown. Its misregulation is tied to diabetes and cancer, making it a research hotspot. Discovered in 1999, it’s a metabolic linchpin.",
  132: "After chemotherapy wipes out immune defenses, G-CSF rebuilds them. This protein spurs white blood cell production, protecting cancer patients from infection. Discovered in 1999, it’s a clinical game-changer.",
  133: "Enolase isn’t just a glycolysis enzyme—it’s a multitasker. On cell surfaces, it moonlights as a receptor for plasminogen, aiding blood clot breakdown. Discovered in 1996, it’s a biochemical double agent.",
  134: "When platelet counts drop, Thrombopoietin sounds the alarm. It ramps up production in bone marrow, and drugs mimicking it treat deficiencies. Discovered in 1997, it’s a blood clotting hero.",
  135: "Glucose-6-phosphate Isomerase drives glycolysis but doesn’t stop there. Outside cells, it doubles as a nerve growth factor, supporting neural repair. Discovered in 1995, it’s a surprising multitasker.",
  136: "Meet the only hormone that makes you hungrier: Ghrelin. Secreted by the stomach, it ramps up appetite before meals. Discovered in 2008, it’s the body’s dinner bell.",
  137: "Hexokinase kickstarts glucose metabolism with a dramatic flair. When glucose binds, its structure shifts like a transformer, locking in fuel for energy. Discovered in 1997, it’s the gatekeeper of cellular power.",
  138: "DIG14 isn’t from nature—it’s a lab-crafted masterpiece. Designed on a computer to bind digitoxin with surgical precision, it proves proteins can be built from scratch. Discovered in 2021, it’s pure human ingenuity.",
  139: "Phosphoglycerate Kinase is a power generator in glycolysis. It churns out ATP as glucose breaks down, fueling cellular work. Discovered in 1993, it’s a quiet but essential energy broker.",
  140: "Cyclin A is the conductor of the cell cycle orchestra. It dictates the timing of DNA replication, ensuring cells divide on cue. Discovered in 1996, it’s a guardian of genetic fidelity.",
  141: "Muscles can’t relax without Sarcoplasmic Reticulum Ca-ATPase. This protein pumps calcium back into storage after contraction, resetting for the next move. Discovered in 2000, it’s a muscle recovery MVP.",
  142: "Adiponectin, a hormone from fat tissue, fights metabolic chaos. Higher levels correlate with lower diabetes risk, acting as a protective shield. Discovered in 2004, it’s a beacon of metabolic hope.",
  143: "The Sodium-Potassium Pump is a cellular workhorse, burning 20-25% of your ATP. It maintains ion balance, keeping cells electrically charged and alive. Discovered in 2013, it’s the unsung hero of every heartbeat.",
  144: "Mood swings? Blame the Serotonin Receptor. It’s the target of antidepressants and psychedelics, shaping emotions and perception. Discovered in 2013, it’s a gateway to the mind.",
  145: "Cyclophilin speeds up protein folding like a molecular chaperone. It’s also the target of cyclosporin, an immunosuppressant crucial for organ transplants. Discovered in 1991, it’s a dual-purpose powerhouse.",
  146: "DIG8-CC is a de novo protein, engineered with coiled-coil perfection. Designed to bind small molecules, it speaks a structural language nature never wrote. Discovered in 2021, it’s a testament to protein design wizardry.",
  147: "Casein Kinase holds the title of the first protein kinase ever discovered. Always active, it phosphorylates targets to regulate cellular clocks and signals. Discovered in 1995, it’s a pioneer of biochemistry.",
  148: "BCL-2 is the ultimate survivalist, blocking programmed cell death. Overexpressed in cancers, it lets rogue cells cheat death. Discovered in 1997, it’s a double-edged sword in oncology.",
  149: "Purine Nucleoside Phosphorylase recycles DNA building blocks called purines. Its deficiency cripples the immune system, causing severe disease. Discovered in 1998, it’s a quiet but critical enzyme.",
  150: "Spectrin gives red blood cells their flexible, disc-like shape. Defects in it cause hereditary spherocytosis, turning cells round and fragile. Discovered in 1993, it’s the scaffold of blood flow.",
  151: "Tears and saliva aren’t just water—they’re armed with lysozyme, a ruthless antibacterial enzyme that shreds bacterial cell walls. Found also in egg whites, it was the first enzyme to have its structure solved in 1965. Discovered by Alexander Fleming before penicillin, it’s a pioneer of molecular defense.",
  152: "Resistin might be the missing link between obesity and diabetes, driving insulin resistance in fat tissue. Its role in human metabolism remains hotly debated, with studies clashing over its impact. Uncovered in 2003, it’s a contentious player in metabolic disease.",
  153: "Trypsin is your gut’s protein shredder, slicing dietary proteins into smaller peptides for absorption. Active in the small intestine, it’s a key digestive enzyme. First identified in 1876 by Wilhelm Kühne, it’s one of the earliest enzymes ever studied.",
  154: "Caffeine’s wake-up call targets the Adenosine A2A Receptor, blocking its sleep-inducing signals in your brain. This receptor normally promotes relaxation, but caffeine steps in as a molecular roadblock. Solved in 2011, it’s the key to understanding your coffee fix.",
  155: "Alpha-Amylase in your saliva kicks off digestion by breaking starch into sugars the moment you chew. Populations with starchy diets often have extra copies of its gene, a neat evolutionary trick. Its structure was detailed in 1990, revealing nature’s carbohydrate crusher.",
  156: "DIG8-CC (Orthogonal Form) is a designed protein so precise it crystallizes in two distinct ways, yet looks perfect in both. This rare feat of packing versatility proves the brilliance of its engineered sequence. Unveiled in 2021, it’s a triumph of protein design over nature’s chaos.",
  157: "Dihydrofolate Reductase builds the raw materials for DNA, churning out key nucleotide components. It’s also the target of methotrexate, a major cancer drug that halts its work to stop cell growth. Characterized in 1982, it’s a linchpin of life and medicine.",
  158: "BAX is the cell’s executioner, punching holes in mitochondrial membranes to trigger programmed death. This apoptosis promoter ensures damaged cells don’t linger. Discovered in 2000, it’s a critical gatekeeper of cellular fate.",
  159: "The proteasome is your cell’s molecular shredder, dismantling damaged or unneeded proteins with brutal efficiency. Shaped like a barrel, it unfolds and destroys tagged targets, a discovery that earned the 2004 Nobel Prize in Chemistry. First detailed in 1997, it’s the ultimate cellular cleanup crew.",
  160: "Keratin builds the tough stuff—your hair, skin, and nails owe their strength to this structural protein. Even rhinoceros horns are pure keratin, a testament to its durability. Its molecular details emerged in 2006, showcasing nature’s toughest fiber.",
  161: "Streptavidin, a bacterial protein, forms the strongest non-covalent bond in nature with biotin. This unbreakable grip is exploited in countless lab techniques for tagging and detection. First studied in 1989, it’s a cornerstone of biotech innovation.",
  162: "Orexin keeps you awake and hungry, regulating both arousal and appetite from the brain. A deficiency can plunge you into narcolepsy, causing sudden sleep attacks. Discovered in 1998, it’s a tiny conductor of vital drives.",
  163: "Reverse Transcriptase, HIV’s notorious enzyme, defies biology’s rules by copying RNA into DNA. It shattered the ‘central dogma’ of molecular biology and is a prime target for AIDS drugs. Solved in 1992, it’s a rogue rewriting life’s code.",
  164: "The Histamine H1 Receptor drives your allergic misery, triggering itching and swelling when activated. Antihistamines like Benadryl block it to bring relief. Its structure, revealed in 2011, unlocks the science of allergy treatment.",
  165: "Cytochrome c shuttles electrons in mitochondria, powering the cellular respiration that keeps you alive. Astonishingly, its structure is nearly identical from yeast to humans, a universal hallmark of life. Detailed in 1991, it’s evolution’s conserved energy broker.",
  166: "De Novo Beta-Helix is a synthetic marvel, a double-stranded beta-helix engineered from scratch with a precision nature rarely achieves. While natural beta-helices are sloppy and scarce, this design is deliberate, strand by strand. Unveiled in 2018, it’s a masterpiece of structural intent.",
  167: "Thymidylate Synthase crafts the ‘T’ in your DNA, supplying a critical nucleotide for genetic code. It’s also a target for the cancer drug 5-fluorouracil, which disrupts its function to halt tumor growth. Solved in 1995, it’s a vital piece of life’s puzzle.",
  168: "p53, dubbed the guardian of the genome, stops damaged cells from turning cancerous by halting their division or triggering death. Mutated in over 50% of human cancers, it’s the most studied protein in oncology. First detailed in 1994, it’s a frontline defender gone rogue too often.",
  169: "Acetylcholinesterase clears the neurotransmitter acetylcholine from synapses at lightning speed, processing 25,000 molecules per second. It’s one of the fastest enzymes known, ensuring nerve signals don’t overstay their welcome. Characterized in 1991, it’s a marvel of synaptic precision.",
  170: "Elastin gives your skin and arteries their bounce, stretching up to 150% before snapping back like a rubber band. It’s the protein behind youthful flexibility. Solved in 2002, it’s nature’s elastic secret.",
  171: "Ribonucleotide Reductase converts RNA building blocks into DNA precursors, a non-negotiable step for genetic replication. It’s also a target for cancer drugs aiming to stop runaway cell division. Detailed in 1999, it’s a cornerstone of life’s blueprint.",
  172: "Alpha-MSH, or melanocyte-stimulating hormone, tweaks skin pigmentation and curbs appetite from the brain. It’s a dual-purpose signaling molecule with subtle but powerful effects. Discovered in 1998, it’s a quiet regulator of color and hunger.",
  173: "Fatty Acid Synthase turns carbs into fat, assembling long lipid chains in a metabolic factory. It’s eyed as a potential target for obesity drugs to slow fat buildup. Solved in 1997, it’s a key player in energy storage.",
  174: "The Cannabinoid CB1 Receptor is the brain’s main docking site for marijuana’s active compounds, shaping their psychoactive punch. It’s the most abundant GPCR in the central nervous system. Revealed in 2016, it’s the gateway to cannabis effects.",
  175: "Acetyl-CoA Carboxylase sets the pace for fat synthesis, acting as the gatekeeper of lipid production. It’s a hot target for research into diabetes and obesity treatments. Detailed in 1997, it’s a metabolic control point with big implications.",
  176: "Imagine building a protein from scratch with a precise 3D blueprint. Mini Protein HEEH-rd4, a de novo miniprotein solved by NMR in 2017, boasts a helix-strand-strand-helix topology that was designed before synthesis. Its structure holds steady even in solution, passing the toughest test of free-floating stability.",
  177: "Acyl-CoA Dehydrogenase kicks off fat burning by breaking down fatty acids. Discovered in 1996, this enzyme is critical for energy production. A deficiency, like MCAD, can tragically lead to sudden infant death.",
  178: "BRCA1 is your DNA’s repair crew, but mutations can spell disaster, raising breast cancer risk. Discovered in 2001, it gained spotlight when Angelina Jolie shared her own mutation in 2013. Its failure can rewrite family histories.",
  179: "Src Kinase, identified in 1999, was the first oncogene product tied to cancer. Originating from a chicken virus, it revealed how kinases drive tumors, sparking a drug revolution. One tiny protein, one giant leap for cancer therapy.",
  180: "Fibronectin acts as the glue linking cells to their extracellular matrix. Discovered in 2003, it plays a starring role in wound healing, knitting tissues back together. Without it, your body’s repair shop would stall.",
  181: "Protein Kinase A, uncovered in 1991, is the pioneer of cAMP-dependent signaling. It was the first kinase to have its structure solved, paving the way for understanding cellular communication. A true trailblazer in protein science.",
  182: "Agouti Protein messes with color and appetite by blocking MSH signaling. Discovered in 1999, it’s why yellow mice with this mutation balloon into obesity. A small tweak, a big waistline.",
  183: "Carnitine Palmitoyltransferase shuttles fats into mitochondria for burning. Discovered in 1999, it’s the gatekeeper of fat oxidation, setting the pace for energy production. If it slows, your metabolism does too.",
  184: "Glutamate Receptor is the brain’s primary excitatory switch, driving neural communication. Discovered in 2009, it’s at the heart of learning and memory. Without it, your thoughts wouldn’t spark.",
  185: "Granzyme B is the immune system’s assassin, unleashed by killer cells to destroy targets. Discovered in 1999, it punches holes in cells and triggers apoptosis. It’s a precise, lethal weapon.",
  186: "Curved Beta-Sheet Protein γ, designed in 2016, is a masterclass in systematic protein engineering. This third variant in its series refined how we predict and build structures. Once partly guesswork, protein design edged closer to true engineering with this one.",
  187: "ERK1/2 Kinase is a linchpin in the MAP kinase cascade, directing cell growth and division. Discovered in 2001, it’s a prime target for cancer drugs. Block it, and rogue cells might stop multiplying.",
  188: "BRCA2 teams up with BRCA1 to repair DNA, safeguarding your genetic code. Discovered in 2002, mutations in it also heighten risks of pancreatic and prostate cancer. It’s a quiet guardian with high stakes.",
  189: "Glutamine Synthetase crafts glutamine while detoxifying ammonia in your body. Discovered in 1994, it’s one of nature’s most tightly regulated enzymes. Every step it takes is watched and controlled.",
  190: "Laminin, discovered in 1999, is a cross-shaped giant in basement membranes. It anchors cells in place, forming the foundation of tissues like skin and organs. Without it, your body’s architecture crumbles.",
  191: "Glutamate Dehydrogenase bridges amino acid and energy metabolism in cells. Discovered in 1992, it’s activated by leucine and tied to insulin secretion. A small player with a big metabolic role.",
  192: "POMC is a hormonal goldmine, splitting into ACTH, MSH, endorphins, and more. Discovered in 2008, this precursor protein shapes stress, pain, and pigmentation. One molecule, many missions.",
  193: "Chymotrypsin, a pancreatic protease discovered in 1967, slices proteins during digestion. It’s the classic model for decoding how enzymes work. Science learned a lot from this gut warrior.",
  194: "GABA-A Receptor is the brain’s main brake, calming neural activity. Discovered in 2014, it’s the target of benzodiazepines, alcohol, and anesthetics. Mess with it, and your mind slows down.",
  195: "Carboxypeptidase A, a zinc-powered digestive enzyme, was discovered in 1967. It was the first zinc enzyme to have its structure solved, revealing metal’s role in catalysis. A shiny milestone in biochemistry.",
  196: "Beta-Sheet Homodimer Design, crafted in 2016, is a de novo protein where two identical chains self-assemble into a symmetric dimer. Designing a monomer is tough; nailing a specific dimer interface is next-level 3D wizardry. Someone mastered spatial thinking here.",
  197: "Thrombin is the blood clotting cascade’s star player, sealing wounds fast. Discovered in 1992, it’s the target of blood thinners like dabigatran. Too much action, and clots turn deadly.",
  198: "Troponin regulates muscle contraction and signals heart trouble when levels spike. Discovered in 2003, its blood test is the gold standard for diagnosing heart attacks. A tiny protein, a lifesaving clue.",
  199: "Elastase chews up elastin in lungs, and when unchecked, it fuels emphysema. Discovered in 1989, smoking disables its inhibitor, wrecking lung tissue. A destructive force with a clear culprit.",
  200: "Claudin seals tight junctions in epithelial cells, keeping barriers leak-proof. Discovered in 2014, it ensures your gut lining doesn’t let unwanted guests through. A tiny gatekeeper with a big job.",
  201: "Your stomach is a cauldron of acid, and pepsin is the chef. This digestive enzyme thrives at pH 2, breaking down proteins into peptides with ruthless efficiency. Discovered in 1991, it’s the powerhouse behind turning your meal into fuel.",
  202: "Ever felt a runner’s high? Thank endorphins, your body’s natural painkillers. These opioid peptides flood your brain during exercise, dulling pain and boosting euphoria. Discovered in 2003, they’re nature’s feel-good fix.",
  203: "HIV Protease is the deadly architect of AIDS, slicing viral proteins to build new viruses. Blocking it with protease inhibitors was a game-changer in treatment. Discovered in 1989, it remains a critical target in the fight against HIV.",
  204: "Nicotine hooks you through the Nicotinic Acetylcholine Receptor, a key player in muscle movement and brain signaling. It was the first neurotransmitter receptor ever identified. Discovered in 2005, it’s a gateway to understanding addiction and neural control.",
  205: "HIV Reverse Transcriptase is the sneak thief that copies HIV’s RNA into human DNA. It’s the target of AZT, the first approved AIDS drug, which jams its machinery. Discovered in 1992, it’s a cornerstone of antiviral strategy.",
  206: "Curved Beta-Sheet Protein δ is a masterpiece of protein engineering, the fourth in a series of deliberately crafted designs. By this stage, scientists were sculpting structures with pinpoint precision, not waiting for nature’s whims. Discovered in 2016, it’s proof humans can play architect at the molecular level.",
  207: "HIV Integrase is the infiltrator that stitches HIV DNA into human chromosomes, sealing the infection. It’s the target of the newest class of AIDS drugs, offering fresh hope. Discovered in 2010, it’s a critical battleground in HIV therapy.",
  208: "Tropomyosin acts like a bouncer for muscle contraction, guarding actin until the right signal arrives. When calcium shows up, it swings open the gate for action. Discovered in 2001, it’s a key regulator of every flex and twitch.",
  209: "Ribonuclease T1, a fungal enzyme, slashes RNA with surgical precision. It was one of the first enzymes to have its full structure mapped out. Discovered in 1989, it’s a pioneer in protein science history.",
  210: "Dystrophin is the scaffold linking muscle fibers to their support matrix, and without it, muscular dystrophy strikes. Spanning 2.4 million base pairs, it’s one of the longest human genes. Discovered in 1998, its absence spells tragedy for muscle integrity.",
  211: "Ribonuclease H chews up RNA in RNA-DNA hybrids, a quiet but essential player in replication. It’s critical for HIV to copy itself, making it a potential drug target. Discovered in 1990, it’s a hidden gear in viral machinery.",
  212: "Enkephalin, a tiny opioid peptide, was the first natural painkiller found in the body. It binds to brain receptors to dull pain and tweak mood. Discovered in 1988, it unveiled how we fight hurt from within.",
  213: "Cytochrome c Oxidase is why you breathe, turning oxygen into water as the final step in cellular respiration. It’s the powerhouse enzyme driving energy production in your cells. Discovered in 1995, it’s the literal end of the line for oxygen.",
  214: "The Insulin Receptor senses insulin and flips the switch for glucose uptake in cells. Defects in it can trigger diabetes, making it a prime target for therapies. Discovered in 1994, it’s central to managing blood sugar chaos.",
  215: "Cytochrome bc1 Complex shuttles electrons in the respiratory chain, fueling cellular energy. It’s also a target for fungicides and antimalarial drugs, disrupting vital processes. Discovered in 1998, it’s a crossroads of biology and medicine.",
  216: "Curved Beta-Sheet Protein ε, the fifth in a groundbreaking series, maps uncharted structural territory in protein design. With five crystal structures in one program, it’s no fluke but a deliberate scientific vision. Discovered in 2016, it showcases human mastery over molecular form.",
  217: "Prostate Specific Antigen (PSA) is a serine protease and a key marker for prostate cancer. Blood tests for PSA help screen for this common disease. Discovered in 1991, it’s a frontline tool in early detection.",
  218: "CAP Protein flips genetic switches in bacteria, activated by cAMP to control gene expression. It’s a textbook case of how microbes regulate their behavior. Discovered in 1991, it’s a cornerstone of molecular biology studies.",
  219: "Tissue Plasminogen Activator is a lifesaver, busting blood clots during stroke emergencies. Administered fast, it can restore blood flow and limit brain damage. Discovered in 1991, it’s a critical weapon in acute care.",
  220: "Fibrinogen is the raw material for blood clots, transforming into a fibrin mesh that traps cells to stop bleeding. It’s the body’s emergency patch kit. Discovered in 1997, it’s vital for wound healing and survival.",
  221: "Urokinase dissolves blood clots, and yes, it was first purified from human urine. It’s a key player in clearing vascular blockages. Discovered in 1987, it’s an odd but effective medical tool.",
  222: "Dynorphin, an opioid peptide, tweaks pain and mood but may also fuel the misery of addiction withdrawal. It’s a darker cousin to feel-good endorphins. Discovered in 1996, it’s a complex piece of brain chemistry.",
  223: "Plasmin is the body’s clot-dissolver, activated from plasminogen when blockages need clearing. It’s a cleanup crew for blood vessels. Discovered in 1991, it balances clotting to keep circulation smooth.",
  224: "Fas Death Receptor signals cells to self-destruct, a grim but necessary process. Immune cells wield it to eliminate infected or rogue targets. Discovered in 2000, it’s a key player in programmed cell death.",
  225: "Factor VIII is the clotting protein missing in hemophilia A, infamous as the ‘royal disease’ tied to Queen Victoria. Without it, bleeding can’t stop. Discovered in 2001, it’s a historic target for treatment innovation.",
  226: "The Ebola Glycoprotein is the deadly handshake of the Ebola virus, studding its surface to invade host cells. It’s the prime target for antibody treatments, a lifeline in outbreaks. Discovered in 2008, it’s a key to unlocking therapies for one of the world’s most feared pathogens.",
  227: "Factor IX, dubbed the Christmas factor after an early patient, is a clotting protein absent in hemophilia B. Without it, even minor injuries can lead to uncontrolled bleeding. Discovered in 1999, it’s central to replacement therapies that save lives.",
  228: "De Novo Beta-Sheet OR664 is a lab-made protein, designed from scratch to fold into a precise beta-sheet structure. Solved by NMR in 2016, it proves computational predictions can create stable proteins in solution. Every residue and hydrogen bond was planned, a triumph of protein engineering.",
  229: "Factor VIIa kickstarts the blood clotting cascade, turning a trickle into a dam. Its recombinant form, discovered in 1995, is a critical treatment for hemophilia patients. This protein is the body’s first responder to bleeding.",
  230: "Lambda Repressor is a viral genetic switch, flipping genes on or off with ruthless precision. Discovered in 1987, it’s a model for decoding how DNA circuits control life. Think of it as a molecular yes-or-no gate.",
  231: "Polyketide Synthase builds complex molecules like antibiotics, nature’s chemical weapons. Discovered in 2007, it’s behind many life-saving drugs we rely on. This protein is a factory for natural product diversity.",
  232: "Von Willebrand Factor glues platelets to damaged blood vessels, stopping bleeds fast. A deficiency triggers the most common bleeding disorder, von Willebrand disease. Discovered in 2006, it’s a cornerstone of hemostasis.",
  233: "Penicillin Acylase crafts penicillin antibiotics, a cornerstone of modern medicine. Discovered in 1995, it’s used industrially to produce semisynthetic versions of these drugs. This enzyme turns raw materials into lifesavers.",
  234: "Substance P screams pain, a neuropeptide released by sensory neurons during injury or inflammation. Discovered in 1991, it’s a key player in how we feel hurt. It’s the body’s alarm system, loud and clear.",
  235: "Beta-Lactamase is the enemy of antibiotics, shredding penicillin-type drugs with brutal efficiency. Discovered in 1992, it’s a major driver of bacterial resistance. This enzyme turns wonder drugs into useless scraps.",
  236: "TNF Receptor orchestrates inflammation and cell death, a double-edged sword in the immune system. Discovered in 1993, its blockers have transformed arthritis treatment. Targeting this protein tames overactive immune responses.",
  237: "CRISPR-Cas9 is a bacterial defense turned gene-editing scalpel, rewriting DNA with precision. Discovered in 2014, it earned the 2020 Nobel Prize at record speed. This protein is revolutionizing biology and medicine.",
  238: "Rabies Glycoprotein coats the rabies virus, enabling its deadly invasion of nerve cells. Discovered in 2002, it’s part of a disease that’s nearly 100% fatal without treatment. This protein is a grim key to a lethal lock.",
  239: "Dihydropteroate Synthase is vital for bacterial folate synthesis, a process halted by sulfonamide antibiotics. Discovered in 1997, it’s a classic drug target. Blocking this protein starves bacteria of essential nutrients.",
  240: "De Novo Beta-Sheet OR485, designed alongside OR664, is another synthetic protein triumph, confirmed by NMR in 2016. It shows that beta-sheet design principles hold across varied sequences. Every fold was predicted, proving protein engineering’s power.",
  241: "Vancomycin Target Protein is the last line of defense for a last-resort antibiotic. Discovered in 1996, it’s outsmarted by VRSA bacteria through resistance mutations. This protein’s vulnerability highlights the antibiotic crisis.",
  242: "Gelsolin snips and caps actin filaments, shaping the cell’s skeleton. Discovered in 1999, its mutations cause Finnish-type amyloidosis, a rare protein buildup disease. This protein keeps cells structured, until it doesn’t.",
  243: "Azurin, a copper-based electron shuttle, zaps energy through bacterial systems. Discovered in 1991, it’s now under study as a potential cancer-killing agent. This tiny protein might pack a therapeutic punch.",
  244: "HU Protein crams bacterial DNA into a tight, organized package. Discovered in 1990, it’s essential for compacting the bacterial chromosome. Think of it as a microbial storage expert.",
  245: "Plastocyanin, a copper protein, ferries electrons during photosynthesis in plant chloroplasts. Discovered in 1983, it’s a critical link in turning light into energy. This blue-hued protein powers green life.",
  246: "Neuropeptide Y ramps up appetite and dials down anxiety in the brain. Discovered in 1991, it’s one of the most abundant neuropeptides we know. This molecule nudges us to eat and relax.",
  247: "Rubredoxin is a bare-bones iron-sulfur protein, stripped to the essentials of electron transfer. Discovered in 1994, it’s among the simplest iron proteins known. Minimalist design, maximal function.",
  248: "Opsin catches light in our eyes, turning photons into vision. Discovered in 2000, its mutations cause color blindness. This protein paints the world we see.",
  249: "Horseradish Peroxidase is a lab workhorse, powering reactions in pregnancy tests and assays. Discovered in 1997, it’s a go-to enzyme for detection and research. This protein turns experiments into answers.",
  250: "Norovirus Capsid forms the shell of the stomach flu virus, ruthlessly contagious. Discovered in 2006, just 18 particles can trigger infection. This protein is a tiny terror behind massive outbreaks.",
  251: "Manganese Peroxidase chews through lignin, the tough scaffold of wood, like a molecular buzzsaw. Found in certain fungi, it’s a key player in breaking down plant material. Its potential to turn plant waste into biofuels could fuel a greener future. Discovered in 1994.",
  252: "Hallucinated Protein 0217 isn’t from nature—it was dreamed up by a neural network in a literal sense. This 2020 creation, with no evolutionary ancestor, folds perfectly and functions after being synthesized. It’s a glimpse into the wild frontier of protein design.",
  253: "Lignin Peroxidase is nature’s wood wrecker, degrading the stubborn lignin in plants. White rot fungi wield it to digest timber, turning solid structures into mush. Discovered in 1993, it’s a quiet hero of decay.",
  254: "Profilin is the logistics manager for actin, delivering monomers to build cellular filaments. It fine-tunes how fast these structures grow, shaping cell movement and form. Discovered in 1992, it’s a backstage star of cytoskeletal dynamics.",
  255: "Laccase oxidizes phenolic compounds with ruthless efficiency, transforming them in nature and industry. It’s a go-to for bioremediation, cleaning up pollutants, and even clarifies wine during production. Discovered in 1998, it’s a versatile chemical workhorse.",
  256: "Casein is the protein backbone of cheese, giving it that signature stretch when melted. It’s the glue holding dairy delights together, from creamy brie to gooey mozzarella. Discovered in 2011, it’s the secret behind every perfect bite.",
  257: "Cellulase dismantles cellulose, the tough fiber in plants, into usable sugars. It’s a linchpin for creating biofuels from agricultural waste, turning trash into energy. Discovered in 1998, it’s a quiet revolutionary in sustainability.",
  258: "VIP, or Vasoactive Intestinal Peptide, widens blood vessels and relaxes muscles with precision. It’s a key regulator in the gut and beyond, easing tension where needed. Discovered in 2000, it’s a silent conductor of bodily calm.",
  259: "ATP Synthase is a molecular turbine spinning at 9000 RPM, crafting ATP, the cell’s energy currency. It’s the smallest motor known, powering life with every turn. Discovered in 1994, it’s a marvel of biological engineering.",
  260: "Phytochrome acts as a plant’s light sensor, detecting day length to time critical events. It dictates when flowers bloom, syncing plants with seasons. Discovered in 2005, it’s nature’s calendar keeper.",
  261: "Glucoamylase slices starch into glucose, fueling industrial processes with sweet simplicity. It’s the enzyme behind corn syrup production, turning complex carbs into liquid gold. Discovered in 1993, it’s a staple of food manufacturing.",
  262: "Rotavirus Capsid forms the outer shell of a virus causing severe diarrhea in children. Vaccines targeting it save half a million lives annually, a staggering triumph. Discovered in 1999, it’s a reminder of science’s life-saving power.",
  263: "Invertase splits sucrose into glucose and fructose, sweetening the deal for candy makers. It’s the magic behind soft, gooey candy fillings that melt in your mouth. Discovered in 1996, it’s a confectioner’s best friend.",
  264: "Mini Protein HHH-rd1, just 40 residues long, is a de novo marvel with three helices and rock-solid stability. Unlike natural proteins this small, which flop around, this 2017 design proves purposeful engineering trumps evolutionary chance.",
  265: "Beta-Glucosidase liberates glucose from various compounds, unlocking hidden sweetness. In winemaking, it releases flavor compounds, enhancing every sip. Discovered in 1995, it’s a subtle artisan of taste.",
  266: "Cofilin slashes through actin filaments, severing and breaking them down for remodeling. It creates fresh ends for new growth, keeping cells dynamic. Discovered in 1998, it’s the cytoskeleton’s ruthless editor.",
  267: "Beta-Galactosidase breaks down lactose, the sugar in milk, into digestible bits. A deficiency causes lactose intolerance, leaving millions bloated and miserable. Discovered in 1994, it’s the key to dairy digestion.",
  268: "Gluten, the wheat protein, gives bread its irresistible chew but triggers celiac disease in some. It’s the structural star of dough, binding it together. Discovered in 2004, it’s both a baker’s ally and a hidden foe.",
  269: "Xylanase dismantles hemicellulose in plant cell walls, softening tough fibers. It’s a workhorse in bread making and paper production, improving texture and efficiency. Discovered in 1994, it’s an unsung industrial hero.",
  270: "Cholecystokinin signals satiety and kickstarts digestion, telling your brain you’re full. It also triggers gallbladder contraction, releasing bile for fat breakdown. Discovered in 2005, it’s a dual-purpose hormone of appetite and action.",
  271: "Pectin Lyase softens plant cell walls by cleaving pectin, a key structural component. It’s behind the ripening of fruits, turning them tender and juicy. Discovered in 1996, it’s nature’s softening agent.",
  272: "Bacteriorhodopsin is a light-driven proton pump, harnessing photons to move energy in microbes. It inspired optogenetics, revolutionizing neuroscience by controlling neurons with light. Discovered in 1997, it’s a bridge from biology to technology.",
  273: "Chitinase breaks down chitin, the tough material in fungal walls and insect shells. Plants use it as a defense weapon against fungal invaders. Discovered in 1994, it’s a frontline soldier in botanical warfare.",
  274: "Cryptochrome senses blue light to regulate circadian rhythms and more. In birds, it aids navigation by detecting Earth’s magnetic field, a biological compass. Discovered in 2004, it’s a multitasking marvel of nature.",
  275: "Hyaluronidase degrades hyaluronic acid, clearing paths in tissues for other molecules. Known as a spreading factor, it helps infections invade by breaking barriers. Discovered in 1993, it’s a double-edged sword in biology.",
  276: "Imagine a virus shell so notorious it shaped modern medicine. The poliovirus capsid forms the protective coat of the polio virus, once a global scourge, now nearly eradicated by vaccines. Its structure, solved in 1985, reveals how viruses assemble with deadly precision.",
  277: "Heparanase is a silent saboteur, slicing through the extracellular matrix to remodel tissues. Its dark side? It aids cancer cells in spreading, making it a prime drug target since its structure was unveiled in 2008.",
  278: "Mini Protein EEHEE-rd3 is a lab-born marvel, a synthetic protein designed from scratch with a mixed alpha-beta fold. Named for its strand-strand-helix-strand-strand pattern, it’s a compact, stable proof of protein engineering. Unveiled in 2017, it shows we can build biology to spec.",
  279: "Collagenase is nature’s demolition expert, breaking down collagen in connective tissues. Medically, it’s harnessed to dissolve scar tissue with surgical precision. Its mechanism was clarified in 1995, unlocking therapeutic potential.",
  280: "Alpha-1-Antitrypsin acts as a molecular bouncer, blocking rogue proteases in the body. Deficiency in this protein, identified in 1996, is a genetic trigger for emphysema, wrecking lung tissue over time.",
  281: "Matrix Metalloproteinase 1 is a tissue architect gone rogue, remodeling the extracellular matrix. It’s implicated in arthritis and cancer metastasis, making it a double-edged sword since its discovery in 1999.",
  282: "Spider Silk Spidroin crafts nature’s toughest fiber, outmuscling steel by weight while stretching like rubber. Solved in 2006, its structure hints at why spiders weave webs stronger than our best synthetics.",
  283: "Gelatinase tears through basement membranes, clearing paths in tissue. Cancer cells exploit it to invade, a grim trick revealed when its structure was solved in 1999. It’s a target for stopping metastasis in its tracks.",
  284: "Gastrin flips the switch on stomach acid production, driving digestion. Overproduction, noted since its 1993 structural insight, triggers Zollinger-Ellison syndrome, causing painful ulcers through acid overload.",
  285: "Acetylcholinesterase from the electric ray Torpedo is a neurotransmitter cleanup crew, breaking down signals at synapses. Since 1991, its structure has been a model for designing drugs targeting nerve disorders.",
  286: "Hemoglobin, the oxygen ferry in your blood, paints it red while sustaining life. Its structure, solved in 1959 by Max Perutz, earned a Nobel Prize as the first protein mapped by X-ray crystallography. It’s the cornerstone of structural biology.",
  287: "Butyrylcholinesterase is your body’s detox agent, metabolizing cocaine and nerve agents in the blood. Discovered in 1999, its structure shows how it neutralizes threats, from drugs to chemical weapons.",
  288: "The Venus Flytrap Domain, named for its plant-like snapping shape, senses signals in many receptors. Since 1997, its structure has revealed how cells detect and respond to their environment with trap-like precision.",
  289: "Paraoxonase is a guardian enzyme, detoxifying organophosphates like pesticides. Its protective role, structurally mapped in 1991, shields us from chemical poisoning in everyday exposures.",
  290: "The HPV Capsid forms the shell of human papillomavirus, a key player in cervical cancer. Vaccines targeting it, based on its 2009 structure, have slashed cancer rates worldwide. Prevention in protein form.",
  291: "Luciferase, the firefly’s glow enzyme, lights up biology labs everywhere. Since 1996, its structure has powered research by illuminating cells under study with bioluminescent magic.",
  292: "Maltoporin is a bacterial gatekeeper, a pore that selectively shuttles sugars into cells. Solved in 1995, it showcases how nature designs channels with picky precision for molecular traffic.",
  293: "Aequorin, a jellyfish protein, senses calcium with a glow, guiding early bioluminescence research. Discovered in 1985, it paved the way for Shimomura’s Nobel-winning work on GFP. A tiny light with huge impact.",
  294: "Zein, a corn storage protein, doubles as a practical powerhouse. Mapped in 1992, it’s used to coat pills and craft biodegradable plastics, turning grain into green tech.",
  295: "Alpha-Lactalbumin teams up with galactosyltransferase to churn out lactose in milk. Its structure, revealed in 1997, shows how it fuels infants with sugar straight from the source.",
  296: "Mini Protein EHEE-rd1 is a computational triumph, a de novo miniprotein engineered for stability under 50 residues. Designed in 2017, it defies thermodynamics with clever folding. Nature didn’t make this; we did.",
  297: "Hepatitis C Polymerase drives Hep C replication, a viral Achilles’ heel. Solved in 2015, it’s the target of breakthrough drugs that now cure this once-incurable disease.",
  298: "Antithrombin shuts down blood-clotting proteases, keeping circulation in check. Since 1991, we’ve known heparin activates it, making this protein central to anti-clotting therapies.",
  299: "Hepatitis B Polymerase fuels Hep B replication, a viral engine. Mapped in 2015, it’s a critical target for antivirals that combat this persistent liver threat.",
  300: "Silkworm Fibroin spins the silk humans have prized for 5,000 years. Its structure, solved in 2005, reveals the molecular secret behind silk’s unmatched strength and sheen.",
  301: "Herpes Thymidine Kinase is the sneaky target of acyclovir, a drug that outsmarts herpes viruses. This enzyme activates acyclovir into a form that halts viral DNA replication. Its discovery in 1995 owes a nod to Gertrude Elion, whose Nobel-winning work gave us this antiviral weapon.",
  302: "MHC Class I is your cell’s billboard, displaying bits of internal proteins to immune cells. If the display looks foreign, as in organ transplants, rejection kicks in due to unique MHC profiles. Discovered in 1987, it’s the root of why your body plays hard to get with donated tissues.",
  303: "CMV Protease is a key player in cytomegalovirus replication, a virus that’s a silent threat to the immunocompromised. This enzyme cleaves viral proteins to assemble new virus particles. Uncovered in 1996, it’s a potential target for antiviral therapies in vulnerable patients.",
  304: "Secretin holds the title of the first hormone ever identified, dating back to 1902. It triggers the pancreas to release bicarbonate, neutralizing stomach acid in the gut. Though this blurb references a 2006 discovery, its true historical debut was by Bayliss and Starling over a century ago.",
  305: "Prostaglandin E Synthase fuels inflammation by churning out prostaglandins, molecules behind pain and swelling. Discovered in 2008, it’s a hot target for next-gen anti-inflammatory drugs. Think of it as a factory we’re trying to shut down without collateral damage.",
  306: "Tetracycline Efflux Pump is bacteria’s bouncer, kicking out tetracycline antibiotics before they can do damage. Discovered in 2002, it’s a major driver of antibiotic resistance. This protein is why some infections laugh in the face of old-school treatments.",
  307: "COX-2 with Inhibitor reveals how selective NSAIDs like celecoxib block pain and inflammation without gut side effects. Captured in 1997, this structure shows the drug snugly blocking the enzyme’s active site. It’s a blueprint for designing kinder painkillers.",
  308: "S1P Receptor, targeted by the MS drug fingolimod, controls immune cell traffic in the body. Discovered in 2012, it helps keep immune cells from attacking nerves in multiple sclerosis. This protein is a gatekeeper we’ve learned to trick for therapeutic gain.",
  309: "Hepatitis B Surface Antigen is the star of the first recombinant vaccine, a game-changer in preventing Hep B. Identified in 1999, it trains the immune system to spot and destroy the virus. This protein turned a deadly infection into a preventable one.",
  310: "Outer Membrane Protein F is a bacterial gatekeeper, forming a unique beta-barrel pore in outer membranes. Discovered in 1995, it controls what enters and exits Gram-negative bacteria. Its structure is a textbook example of nature’s engineering in tough microbial walls.",
  311: "Cruciferin is the heavyweight storage protein in canola and rapeseed, making up the bulk of canola meal. Found in 2003, it stores nutrients for the plant’s growth. It’s the unsung hero behind this crop’s value as livestock feed.",
  312: "Curved Beta-Sheet Protein α is a lab-made marvel, its beta-sheet bent to a precise angle by design, not evolution. Discovered in 2016, it proves we can engineer protein shapes with mathematical precision. Unlike nature’s trial and error, this curvature was calculated to perfection.",
  313: "Phosphotriesterase is a biochemical shield, breaking down nerve agents like sarin into harmless bits. Discovered in 1994, it holds promise for protecting against chemical weapons. This enzyme could be a frontline defense in a toxic world.",
  314: "Plasminogen Activator Inhibitor keeps blood clot breakdown in check, but high levels spell trouble. Discovered in 1991, it’s a predictor of heart attack risk when overactive. This protein is a silent player in cardiovascular danger zones.",
  315: "Resilin is the insect world’s rubber band, giving fleas the power to jump 150 times their height. Discovered in 2002, this super-elastic protein absorbs and releases energy with insane efficiency. It’s nature’s blueprint for biological springs.",
  316: "CD8 T Cell Receptor is the lookout for killer T cells, spotting infected or cancerous cells for destruction. Discovered in 1991, it’s a key target for cutting-edge cancer immunotherapies. This protein helps turn your immune system into a precision weapon.",
  317: "Motilin revs up gut motility, pushing food through your digestive tract. Discovered in 2012, it’s mimicked by the antibiotic erythromycin to treat sluggish digestion. This hormone keeps things moving, literally.",
  318: "Myoglobin stores oxygen in muscles, giving meat its red hue, and made history in 1958. It was the first protein structure solved at atomic resolution, a landmark in biochemistry. This muscle protein opened the door to seeing biology in exquisite detail.",
  319: "EPO Receptor Complex shows how erythropoietin signals the body to pump out red blood cells. Captured in 1998, it reveals the molecular handshake that boosts blood production. This structure is key to understanding treatments for anemia.",
  320: "Hsp90 is a molecular babysitter, stabilizing signaling proteins, including many that drive cancer. Discovered in 2006, it’s a prime target for cancer drugs aiming to disrupt tumor growth. This chaperone’s overprotectiveness can be a deadly flaw.",
  321: "Adenovirus Hexon forms the shell of the common cold virus, a structure hacked for good. Discovered in 1991, modified adenoviruses now serve as vaccine vectors. This protein turns a pesky pathogen into a delivery tool for immunity.",
  322: "Porin broke ground as the first membrane channel structure solved in 1991. It proved membrane proteins could be crystallized, a massive leap for structural biology. This bacterial pore opened a window into how membranes control molecular traffic.",
  323: "Glycinin is soybean’s storage protein, the key to tofu’s firm texture when precipitated. Discovered in 2004, it packs nutrients for the plant and protein for your plate. This humble molecule is a cornerstone of soy-based foods.",
  324: "Curved Beta-Sheet Protein β is part of a designed series, tweaking beta-sheet geometry to map protein architecture rules. Discovered in 2016, it helped prove we can control curvature from first principles. This systematic approach is quietly reshaping how we explore protein design.",
  325: "Oxygenase slips oxygen into molecules, transforming them with precision. Discovered in 2008, it’s a promising tool for green chemistry, enabling cleaner reactions. This enzyme could help industry oxidize without the environmental mess.",
  326: "Imagine surviving in water cold enough to freeze blood. Antifreeze proteins in Arctic fish bind to ice crystals, stopping them from growing and keeping the fish alive in subzero seas. Discovered in 1998, these proteins are nature’s ultimate cryoprotectants.",
  327: "Some bacteria turn frost into a weapon with ice nucleation proteins. These proteins trigger ice crystal formation, damaging plant cells so the bacteria can feast on the released nutrients. Discovered in 1990, they’re a chilling example of microbial strategy.",
  328: "Complement C3 is the linchpin of an immune system older than antibodies themselves. It tags pathogens for destruction and rallies other immune players to attack. Discovered in 1991, it’s a cornerstone of our ancient defense network.",
  329: "Your heart doesn’t just pump—it secretes a hormone called atrial natriuretic peptide to lower blood pressure. This groundbreaking discovery in 2003 showed the heart as an endocrine organ, regulating fluid balance with precision.",
  330: "Alpha-fetoprotein acts like fetal albumin, but it’s also a red flag for liver cancer in adults. Blood tests rely on it as a tumor marker. Discovered in 2004, it bridges development and disease detection.",
  331: "Growth hormone receptor is the gatekeeper for growth signals in your body. Mutations here can lead to Laron syndrome, a rare form of dwarfism. Discovered in 1992, it’s key to understanding height and development.",
  332: "Small heat shock proteins are cellular bodyguards, preventing protein clumping under stress. When mutated, they’re linked to cataracts and heart muscle disease. Discovered in 2001, they’re vital for keeping proteins in line.",
  333: "The TMV coat protein forms the protective shell of tobacco mosaic virus, the first virus ever identified in 1892. Studied since 1989, it’s a classic model for understanding viral structure and assembly.",
  334: "Connexins are the architects of cellular communication, forming gap junctions that let small molecules zip between cells. Discovered in 1997, these pores are essential for syncing heartbeats and nerve signals.",
  335: "Legumin is the powerhouse protein packed into legume seeds like peas and beans. Discovered in 2002, it’s a major nutritional player, fueling growth from seedling to table.",
  336: "De Novo Protein 0515 isn’t from nature—it’s a lab-designed masterpiece, compact and stable, proven by NMR. By 2021, creating synthetic proteins like this was a streamlined process, not a fluke. It’s protein engineering at its finest.",
  337: "Dioxygenase enzymes let bacteria munch on pollutants, breaking them down for energy. Discovered in 1995, they’re nature’s cleanup crew, tackling environmental toxins with precision.",
  338: "Annexins are a family of proteins that latch onto cell membranes when calcium is around. Discovered in 1990, they play roles in everything from blood clotting to inflammation control.",
  339: "Barnacle cement protein is nature’s underwater super-glue, sticking tight in the harshest conditions. Discovered in 2006, it’s inspiring new surgical adhesives that work in wet environments.",
  340: "C-reactive protein is the body’s alarm bell for inflammation, spiking up to 1000-fold during infection. Discovered in 1996, it’s a go-to blood test marker for detecting acute illness worldwide.",
  341: "BNP, or brain natriuretic peptide, screams ‘heart stress’ when levels climb in the blood. Discovered in 2004, it’s a critical marker for diagnosing heart failure fast.",
  342: "Albumin reigns as the most abundant protein in blood, ferrying drugs and hormones while stabilizing pressure. Discovered in 1989, it’s the unsung workhorse of circulation.",
  343: "Prolactin receptor flips the switch for milk production during breastfeeding. Discovered in 1998, it’s the key to lactation, linking hormone signals to maternal biology.",
  344: "Protein disulfide isomerase ensures proteins fold with the right disulfide bonds, like a molecular quality inspector. Discovered in 1998, it prevents misfolded messes in the cell’s protein factory.",
  345: "Bluetongue virus capsid forms the shell of a devastating sheep disease, wreaking havoc on livestock. Discovered in 1998, it’s a critical target for understanding and fighting this viral scourge.",
  346: "Aquaporin channels shuttle 3 billion water molecules per second across cell membranes, earning Peter Agre a Nobel Prize. Discovered in 1997, they’re the plumbing system of life.",
  347: "Kinesin is the cell’s delivery truck, walking along microtubules at 100 steps per second to haul cargo. Discovered in 1996, it’s a marvel of molecular motion powering cellular logistics.",
  348: "Ara h 1 is the notorious peanut allergen behind most allergic reactions to peanuts. Discovered in 1999, it’s a prime culprit in food allergy research.",
  349: "Photosystem I turns sunlight into chemical energy in plants with near-perfect efficiency. Discovered in 2001, it’s a core engine of photosynthesis, fueling life on Earth.",
  350: "Hallucinated Protein 0738 was dreamed up by a neural network, then crystallized to match its digital blueprint perfectly. Discovered in 2021, it’s proof that computers can invent proteins—and humans can make them real.",
  351: "Visfatin, a fat tissue enzyme, moonlights as a hormone with a surprising twist. It’s actually a key player in NAD biosynthesis, fueling cellular energy processes. Discovered in 2005, it links metabolism to signaling in ways we’re still unraveling.",
  352: "Ubiquitin is the cell’s grim reaper, tagging doomed proteins for destruction. Found in every eukaryotic cell—hence its name—it’s a universal cleanup crew. Its discovery in 1987 and role in cellular regulation earned a Nobel Prize.",
  353: "Mussel Foot Protein is nature’s underwater glue, sticking to surfaces even in the wettest conditions. Discovered in 2004, it’s inspiring bioadhesives for medical and industrial use. Marine mussels owe their grip to this marvel.",
  354: "Lactoferrin, an iron-binding protein, is a frontline defender in breast milk. It shields infants from infection with its antimicrobial punch. Discovered in 1993, it’s a cornerstone of early immunity.",
  355: "Adrenomedullin, a peptide that dilates blood vessels, was first spotted in an adrenal gland tumor. Discovered in 2012, it regulates blood pressure and protects tissues under stress. It’s a small molecule with big cardiovascular impact.",
  356: "Beta-Lactoglobulin dominates whey protein in cow’s milk but is absent in human milk. Discovered in 1997, it’s often behind dairy allergies in kids. Its role? Still a bit of a mystery beyond structure.",
  357: "The Leptin Receptor binds the appetite hormone leptin, but when it’s defective, severe obesity strikes. Discovered in 2010, it’s a gatekeeper of hunger signals. A broken receptor means the brain never gets the ‘stop eating’ memo.",
  358: "BiP, or GRP78, is the endoplasmic reticulum’s bodyguard, folding proteins and sensing stress. Discovered in 1996, it triggers emergency responses when the ER is overwhelmed. Think of it as a cellular smoke alarm.",
  359: "Foot-and-Mouth Virus is a devastating livestock pathogen, notoriously contagious. The 1967 UK outbreak alone killed 6 million animals, showing its brutal reach. Discovered in 1989, it remains a major agricultural threat.",
  360: "Potassium Channels are picky pores, letting only potassium ions slip through cell membranes. Roderick MacKinnon’s 2003 Nobel-winning work revealed their stunning selectivity mechanism. Discovered in 1998, they’re vital for nerve and muscle function.",
  361: "The DNA Double Helix, unveiled in 1953, is the elegant spiral that encodes life itself. Watson and Crick’s iconic model relied on Rosalind Franklin’s critical X-ray data. It’s the blueprint of every living thing.",
  362: "Dynein, a motor protein, marches the opposite way to kinesin along cellular tracks. Discovered in 2012, it’s one of the largest protein complexes known. It hauls cargo in cells with heavyweight precision.",
  363: "Patatin, a potato storage protein, doubles as a lipase enzyme, breaking down fats. Discovered in 2005, it’s a multitasker in tuber biology. Potatoes rely on it for energy and defense.",
  364: "Photosystem II is the planet’s oxygen factory, splitting water to release the air we breathe. Discovered in 2004, it powers photosynthesis in plants and algae. Every breath you take owes it a debt.",
  365: "Sequence-Model Designed Protein marks a revolution, crafted by deep learning from sequence alone—no structure needed. Discovered in 2020, it skips traditional design steps, turning raw code into stable proteins. This is protein engineering’s new frontier.",
};
